segments.text: Political science, who came here from the northeast, looked very, very sophisticated, sounded very sophisticated.

At its first meeting in the academic council, which was composed of deans and department heads and vice presidents, and this was during the 60s when there were campus disruptions around the nation, very few here

This man came in at his first academic council meeting saying that A&M was sitting on a powder keg, it was about to explode, that the students were near white, and that he was the only one on the campus who recognized this, and the only one that the students had confidence that they could share their concerns with.

But that didn't exactly get him off to the best start with deans and department heads who had been here for a number of years who really thought they had some idea about what A&M was like and were awed in admiration about this man who had been here for a month and understood so much more than they did.
Later, this same person
came into Dean Hubert's office when I was there.
This was probably three years later or something like that.
He had not adjusted A&M much better, nor had A&M adjusted him very well.
And I don't remember what the topic was, but I remember the man saying, Dean Hubert, if you don't agree to this, I'll have no choice other than to submit my resignation.
And very deliberately.
Dean Hubert opened the bottom right-hand drawer of his desk, took out a blank sheet of paper and said, Professor Department Head, I accept your resignation.
The Department Head was absolutely shocked and had no choice other than to follow through with what he just said.
And that convinced me forever and ever that I would never make a threat that I wasn't willing to live with.
I've heard some stories about faculty members who apparently came here with fraudulent resumes, vitas, etc., and this being called to Dean Hubert's attention.
Can you share any examples of that?
Well, one of them was a man who came here and he was the director of the Creative Application of Technology in Education, CATE.
And Dean Hubert was always interested in educational technology.
And I'll come back later to more of that.
But this man came in with electronic teaching devices, television, and all that, and strongly opinionated.
And there were some people who

did not respond very well to him and did some checking and found out that he had falsified his doctoral degree from UCLA and when Frank Hubert confronted him with this, the man's response was, I thought I earned a PhD.
And he was gone pretty quickly and he did not last very long.
We had another person in education psychology who came in with a
prolific list of publications.
Just overwhelming.
And after having several graduate students be surprised by some of the statements that the man made, they started checking his list of publications and found that it was probably 80% fraudulent.
And again, he left very quickly and surprisingly enough went to a more lucrative job in private industry.
Alright, now let's go back to your trail.
You became the associate dean of liberal arts and the dean was then?
David Maxwell.
Describe, Dave, his style.
David Maxwell came in from Indiana University.
And he was wound very tight.
He was very outgoing, casual in his approach, yet high standards.
had his North Carolinian charm.
I think he was from North Carolina.
He made people feel very much at ease.
The biggest surprise I got from David was one fairly wintery day, I guess.
We had one of our rare snow falls and so we all got to work and about nine o'clock got the phone call and it was David Maxwell.
And I said, yes.
And he said, what are you doing at work?
And I said, well, I don't know what you're asking.
I work here.
He said, well, what about the snow?
And I said, well, what about it?
He said, who else is there?
And I said, well, let me put it this way.
You're the only one not here.
And so with my Texas background, thinking that someone who'd been in Indiana for a while would not be the least bit perturbed, he said, well, why don't you send everyone home?
And I said, well, why would we send anyone home?
I said, you know, it's really great, because there are almost no people here.
We're getting a lot of work done.
And by this afternoon, the snow will be gone.
So it'll be a lot safer for them to go home at the regular time.
He said, I'll see you in just a few minutes.
About 15 minutes, he was there in the office.
Day worked.
He was an economist.
And the economics department was one of the rising stars in the College of Liberal Arts, as far as the reputation of the faculty members.
But like I said, the thing I remember most about Day
His charm, his warmth, and his standards.
Key decisions, plus or minus, you remember during those years?
I think probably the key decision was, again,
allocation of resources to the Economics Department because it received a real disproportionate share there for a while.

But it was one of those areas that I think Frank Hubert had been directly involved in highlighting is this is one of the departments that we really wanted to bring to the forefront within the College of Liberal Arts.
Q Do you have any idea how that decision came and with them?
A I really don't.
I would like to know.
It may have been one of those that the time was right, and certainly we went with a more conservative economist.
I think that fit in with the ideas of a lot of the members of the Board of Regents, so I would suspect that they were involved in that.
Certainly it was not on the liberal side.
I've heard stories from Neil Greenhut
that when he came for an interview that President Rutter gave him a long lecture about not being liberal, liberal, liberal, which was a good deal of a waste of time saying that to Greenwald.
He certainly wasn't going to be liberal.
That economics emphasis began under Hubert.
Under Hubert.
And then continued under Maxwell.
That's right.
Would the fact that Maxwell was an economist, reckon that had anything to do with his being selected as dean?
I don't think it hurt him.
Okay.
That's the answer I would have given.
Because as far as I recall, it was a real search.
Yes.
And House of the Liberal Arts was housed in those days?
Still in the activity building.
Okay.
Well, take it back.
Take that back.
I guess by that time, we had moved into Rudder Tower.
Who were the key staff members in the college?
Were there key people in the office?
Peggy Ritchie was there who went with education.
Mrs. Frank Lowe, when I first went to the office.
That was one of the stories, again, that I enjoyed.
Because when I went there, there was a little half moon behind the academic building that had reserved parking.
And so Mrs. Franklow told me what I would need to do to get my reserved parking.
And I said, Mrs. Franklow, I really don't need reserved parking.
I get here early enough that it's not a problem.
And I don't need to park right there.
And I don't move my car during the day.
And so I don't really need it.
And I remember her saying, Barry,
clearly Dean McCandless, the associate dean, has always had a reserved parking space.
And I said, you know, Ms. Frankl, I think I'd really like to get one of those reserved parking spaces.
So anyway, I learned that very quickly.
After Mrs. Frankl retired, who, and Peggy Ritchie goes to education, I'm trying to remember who,
Mrs. Spinner.
Who was the, was there an assistant dean?
Henry Pope was an assistant dean part of the time.
Jack Humphreys, who went from here to Sam Houston and then became president.
Saul Ross.
And maybe Ed Hunts was also, and dies as a young man.
Yes, really an outstanding, later graduate, really quality person.
So mostly, Dean Hubert used doctoral students to do a kind of a business type of arrangement as assistant deans.
Now then, in liberal arts, was there an assistant dean when you and Maxwell were working together?
Rufus Waters served as.
What were his duties?
more along the business aspects of it.
Alright.
Give me a typical summary of your specific task as Associate Dean of Liberal Arts.
Primarily, it was related to student affairs, because again, at that point, all the undeclared majors in the university were under Liberal Arts, and so I had the direct responsibility for those
all the student programs, and a fair amount to do with the curriculum, but primarily the student programs.
There must have been some nobody else would believe that it really happened type stories with some students.
Well, you know, I'm not sure.
I'll tell you two quick stories for the far ends of the spectrum.
Because I would use graduate students to help advise and sometimes counsel the students.
And some of them were fairly severe.
We had one student who was the only one in all the time I've been involved in higher education that told people that he would never
to be asked to wait, because I truly believed him to be suicidal.
And I had a graduate student who wanted to be a clinical psychologist named Jan Werner.
And so I talked to Jan.
I said, Jan, are you really sure that you want to be a clinical psychologist?
And she was absolutely certain that she did.
She wound up seeing this student several times because he came in and was really, really disturbed that we did everything we could to get him involved with the counseling center.
But still he had a lot of problems.
And so one day he came in and he had sort of latched on to Jan. And Jan almost shuddered when he came through the door.
And she did her job and did it well.
But when she left, I said, Jan, now think about it.
Would you like to spend the rest of your life, professional life, dealing with six to eight of those people every day with that level of difficulty?
And she left here to become the counseling director at Southwest Louisiana.
So she became a counseling psychologist rather than a clinical psychologist.
But there were a lot of students who would come back later and say, Dean McCown, I want to thank you because without you I would never have graduated from A&M.
And several of you would wonder, what in the world did I do?
No way.
One where I really flubbed up, I had a student who had just gone on academic probation.
And his name was something like Schultz, and he was from Schulenburg, and he was failing the first semester of freshman German for the third time.
And so I thought, well, I'll start out being a little light-hearted.
And I said, why in the world are you having so much difficulty in German?
I said, isn't it kind of embarrassing with a name like Schultz from Schulenburg, and you're from German for the third time?
And he said, well, it's damn sure not inherited.
And I said, well, forget the humor.
And I said, well, do you mind telling me why you chose German?
He said, well, I've got to take some kind of language.
And he said, my brother told me that it would probably take me eight semesters to pass four.
And I said, well, did you just really want to learn German because of your heritage?
Or no, I just had to take something.
I thought I'd take that.
And I said, well.
You are a psychology major.
He said, yes.
I said, do you realize you don't have a language requirement?
He said, oh my god, I'll kill you.
And his brother was a history major who did have a language requirement.
But this kid had signed up for Germany three times, apparently never looked at his catalog.
Apparently, his advisor had never asked him why he was doing this.
So he had lost 12 hours of grade points on a course he didn't like, didn't want, and didn't really need to earn his degree.
So you can do a lot of things to help students avoid difficulty.
And one of my lines was, it's a lot easier to stay out of the hole than it is to get out of the hole.
So there were a lot of things that were not overwhelming in the cosmic theme of the world.
But meant a lot to individual students.
So primarily you were the chief student advising officer.
That's right.
For all of liberal arts and for all of the undeclared majors.
So you didn't have to deal with the, normally with the faculty matters.
To an extent.
Because again, basically at that time the dean's office was essentially a two-man show.
And so whatever the
Didn't want to do it.
I did.
But one of the things that I did appreciate about them, really everyone I've ever worked for, and I feel blessed with, they gave me my area of responsibility and they let me do it.
I don't feel I was ever suddenly gassed.
I never felt that I lacked the authority to do what I was doing.
And all those received a lot of support and I was grateful for that.
They weren't looking over my shoulder.
During that era,
According to the way students thought of it, what were the tough majors and the easy majors on campus?
Were there any, supposing?
Well, somewhat facetiously, engineering was thought of as pre-business.
Engineering, I think, was always thought of as one of the tough majors.
I think most of the areas of science, particularly physical sciences, were thought of as demanding.
Math was always thought of to be a tough major.
I think that at that point, business was not considered to be one of the most demanding.
Agriculture, several were.
more humane than some of the others.
Local arts, education were the ones that, the ones that were not science and technology oriented were often viewed to be the ones that were a little less demanding.
I make believe that I didn't know anything about the registration system.
Describe student registration in a typical semester.
When I came, we did the mass registration, and most often at SEVISA, which I'm one of the few people in the world who really thought was pretty good and enjoyed.
Because in the time that you could get most of the faculty together in one building and have a chance to walk around and see your colleagues and visit, there was a lot of social interaction.
among the people, the students, and the faculty.
And every student had to get their assignment signed off by the associate dean, as well as a departmental representative.
So in a lot of ways, there was a lot of opportunity for personal involvement.
And one of the things that I thought was regrettable, there were a lot of people who thought that was the only time that people got any advisable.
As an undergraduate, I had
always this with Carl Landis.
I knew what I was going to sign up for.
So when I went over there, it was just the formality of going through it.
If you can't get this, you had plan B and all that.
But it was just a mass coming together.
One of the things I remember that bothered me early was there was one sheet that had like eight different sections of it.
And you had to fill it out.
And you had to write your name on each one of them and your address.
And I thought, my gosh.
I still got the same name.
I still got the same address.
And so anyway, technology has helped eliminate that.
Again, one of the stories, a true story that I enjoyed, had a man named Russ Weider in physical education.
He was a combatives expert.
He had been a professional boxer, a professional wrestler.
He had given platform diving exhibitions.
And according to Russ, he was one of the first 24
nationally accredited fencing masters in the United States.

And I used to get a bad time about fencing, but one day, a student was coming through in the summer to register for the fall, and he had to take a physical education course, and he wasn't too involved in that.
And he was asking about the different things he could do and that he could take, and one of the things in the list was fencing.
And his response was, I damn sure won't do that.
I've done that all summer for my daddy.
So I remember asking Russ if he'd be teaching barbed wire or chain link next semester.
Now, do I remember that the assistant or associate deans kind of all sat near an exit area and you kind of, after you got your schedule done?
Everyone had to come through.
You had to sign off on the number of hours and the courses they were taking.
So we looked at every one of them that went through there.
All right, now let's jump back before coeds were here in very large numbers.
summer school.
How did summer school differ from the two main semesters?
Well, I think the main difference was we started at 7 o'clock in the morning.

No air conditioning, and so the sun was up early, and we were up early, and we would go to our classes, and most of the summer school was over by noon because it got so hot in the buildings that you couldn't learn or teach very well.
Am I correct that
Only the library was air-conditioned?
I don't think it was even air-conditioned then.
I think that was one of the early ones.
I remember graduating in G. Raleigh White, and I was so dumb that I wore a suit under my gown and thought I would die.
It was so hot.
Air-conditioning was relatively late by my value system.
Right, so you're with Maxwell for about how long?
You're in liberal arts.
About a year and a half, and then I came involved in the cell study and did that part of the time, too.
Yes, yes, yes.
Describe that.
What did that whole effort include?
This is 1962.
No, no, no, 1972.
Well, it was not long after...
Jack Williams came.
And I know I've told you the story about how I found out that I was going to be the director.
No.
Did I tell you that?
I don't remember that.
Well, I had been asked to serve on one of the committees.
And we had a meeting of the academic council in the conference room in the library.
And Gordon Sweet from the Southern Association came down.
And Horace Byers was there.
John Calhoun.
Wayne Hall, I believe.
But anyway, Gordon Sweet was not very sweet.
He was saying that what A&M proposed was an absolute full-fledged flaming disaster and Southern Association probably wouldn't approve the way that A&M was proposing to do it.
And so Horace Byers said, well, Gordon, I'm glad you brought that up because that's not what we're going to do.
Said, what you have is not right at all, and Chuck McCandless is going to be the director of the self-study.
And that was the first I'd ever heard of it.
I was not asked.
Incidentally, I told this story not very long ago at our coffee meeting, and John Calhoun says, I'm the guy who messed it up.
So anyway, after we got through, Bill Barzak,
And I, and Byers, and probably a couple other went over to meet with Garden Suite.

And so with great skill, I picked out members of the steering committee, and the only one who had any experience on any accreditation was Bill Barzak, who had an editorial responsibility in the previous self-study meeting.
So we got people who, Tim Brundage and Chuck Sampson,
Some others, none of them had any knowledge of the cell study.

And because we knew so little about it, at least we were committed by the Southern Association for having a good cell study, which worked out well, because in one of my first meetings with Jack Williams about the cell study, he told me, Chuck, I know more about cell studies than anybody in the country.
And he probably did.
And I thought,
I know less than anyone in the country.
And I know I was right.
But it was really a worthwhile learning experience for all of us, because it gives you an opportunity to learn a lot about all aspects of the university.
And what was most enjoyable from my point of view was that for some strange reason, Bill and I were asked to meet
almost every time there was a group looking at research in the university.
At one of the meetings they were in there and they were really bad mouthing the administration of A&M because the administration always gives lip service to the importance of research
But look who gets all the rewards, and it's always the teaching faculty."
And I literally laughed out loud.
I said, I'm sorry, but you got to recognize, this is a side of the coin I have never seen before.
But they were just as sincere as they could be that they thought researchers were neglected.
And the other thing that was enjoyable for someone from liberal arts and education was there was no agreement as to what research is.
other than it's what that particular faculty member did.
But you take the people in social sciences, their research was so different from people in cotton genetics, and that was so different from physics.
Now, this self-study effort took about how long?

about two years so you were detached from your associate deeming i was i started out doing both and then and it was housed where uh in the reed mcdonald building and were there did you have a key associate bill barzak all right what about the person did you have some people doing the paperwork that were
secretaries, staffers that were particularly critical?
Marilyn Melcher was one who did cover the work and she was just a lovely, lovely person and did a really good job.
Did y'all have any important recommendations?
If in hindsight now you agree?
Oh, I'd have to think back.
I know that we were very pleased because almost everything that we recommended was accomplished before the visiting committee came.
And we really did, I believe, and this may not be totally objective, but I hope it is, we had a lot of involvement of a lot of people.
And I think it made a significant difference in the development.
I'd have to go back and look at some of the things that were recommended.
Because I remember saying at the very beginning that if people believe that what they do makes a difference,
then they'll be willing to do it again.
If they feel like that it doesn't, then they're not going to be very enthused.
And that was one of the major complaints going back to what I said about Garden Suite.
The way it was originally set up, it was very heavily administrator-oriented.
And one of the things that I heard somewhere in the South State
that I really think was important.
That is, the administration should keep its head in and its hands off.
And Jack Williams, again, being the person that he was and the familiarity of himself, did it extremely well.
I don't know about your case, but in my case, I wasn't aware of a self-study in the early 60s.
There must have been one every 10 years, but I wasn't aware of it.
And I certainly was the one that you worked on.
Let's go back and talk about leadership.
Earl Rutter, describe his style and manner.
He had a military style.
He was very much a believer in a strong administration.
I think he believed that there really was a serious business aspect to a university that had to be considered.
I think Earl Rudder was clearly a man for his time.
I don't believe that A&M could be the university it is today without Earl Rudder having been where he was when he was.
Why?
I agree with you, but why?
of a number of reasons.
One is that for the former students in particular, that Earl Rudder was a real Aggie, in quotes.
And whatever that means to any one of them, he was one.
There was never any doubt that he was a real Aggie and that what he wanted for A&M had to be right for A&M.
If he said that it was okay for A&M to have optional
military training, then it must be okay.
If it was okay for women to come to A&M, then it must be okay.
Someone without the strong convictions about A&M proposing those very same things would have had great difficulty.
We had a president who I did not know well because I was too
But what I didn't know was very positive, it was David Morgan.
And I think David Morgan impressed me, at least, as someone similar to Jack Williams.
He was just too soon.
Yeah, he was too soon.
And what he proposed for A&M was not well received at all.
Earl Rudder,
had, I think, some difficulty with some of the faculty in that he was not an academician.
Earl Rudder was not a polished
